### Methodological Note

**Lytton Strachey's** observation frames the acknowledgments:

> "Every history worthy of the name is, in its own way, as personal as poetry, and its value ultimately depends upon the force and the quality of the character behind it."

- Writing history requires organizing unfamiliar facts into coherent narrative
- Developing logical relationships between facts
- Communicating results to interest broad readership
- Cannot be solitary work — requires collaboration

### The Author's Approach

- **Peter L. Bernstein** emphasizes this is personal history
- Relies heavily on editorial partnership and scholarly collaboration
- Draws on economic history expertise of advisors
- Integrates literary quality with factual rigor
- Takes full responsibility for remaining errors (despite **Charlie Kindleberger's** objection to this convention)

